Telfairia occidentalis

    Authority   Hook. f.
      Family    Magnoliopsida:Dilleniidae:Violales:Cucurbitaceae
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 10307

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A vigorous, climbing vine with stems up to 10 m in
   length. The leaves are composed of 3-5 palmately arranged leaflets, the
   terminal leaflet being up to 15 cm in length. The fruit is pale green,
   with waxy deposit, strongly ribbed at maturity, up to 25 cm in diameter
   and 3-6 kg in weight and with light yellow, fibrous flesh. The seeds
   are flattened, about 3.5 cm in diameter and each fruit produce about
   30-70 seeds. USES Cultivated for its edible seeds and young shoots and
   leaves. The seeds are cooked and eaten like beans and the shoots and
   leaves are eaten like vegetables. GROWING PERIOD Perennial vine. The
   first harvest of female shoots and leaves may begin 80-90 days from
   sowing, and up to 15 harvests may be obtained during the following
   120-160 days. Fruits mature about 120-150 days from sowing. COMMON
   NAMES Fluted pumpkin, Fluted gourd, Telfairia nut, Calabaza costillada,
   Iroko, Krobonko, Oroko, Pondokoko, Gonugbe, Oysternut, Okongebong, Igu,
   Kwerne. FURTHER INF Tolerant to elevations up to 1000 m in the tropics.
   Prefer humid conditions.

   Sources
   SOURCES (Telfairia occidentalis H.f.)
   Tindall H 1983 pp 184-186 [TEXT, FER, LIG, TEMP]
   Roecklein J 1987 pp 497 [USE]
   Hackett C 1982 pp 69 [FER]
   Duke J 1975 pp 29 [PH, RAIN, TEMP]

